## Dimitrios S. Nikolopoulos

Dimitrios Nikolopoulos is the John W. Hancock Professor of Engineering at Virginia Tech, where he imparts knowlege and enables student discovery as Professor in the Department of Computer Science, and Professor by courtesy in the Department of Electrical and Computer Engineering. His research in Computer High-Performance Computing and Computer systems has not only influenced academic circles but also left a significant mark on industry standards and commercial software products. 

His contributions have been integrated into the [OpenMP parallel programming standard](https://www.openmp.org), [RedHat Enterprise Linux](https://www.redhat.com/en/technologies/linux-platforms/enterprise-linux),  and a variety of system software products, including parallelizing compilers, in-memory databases, and data stream processing systems. His work has also spurred innovation in numerous experimental operating systems and programming languages for multicore and multithreded compute servers. More details about his scholarly work are available in his profiles on [DBLP](https://dblp.org/pid/50/1235.html), [Google Scholar](https://scholar.google.com/citations?user=PkCuYUQAAAAJ&hl=en), [ORCID](https://orcid.org/0000-0003-0217-8307), and [Scopus](https://www.scopus.com/authid/detail.uri?authorId=7004096576).

As a dedicated educator, Dimitrios shapes minds through courses in [Computer Organization](https://cs.vt.edu/Undergraduate/courses/CS2506.html), [Systems and Networking Capstone](https://cs.vt.edu/Undergraduate/courses/CS4284.html), [Multiprocessor Programming](https://cs.vt.edu/Graduate/Courses/GradCourseDescriptions.html#CS510) and [Warehouse-Scale Computing](https://cs.vt.edu/Graduate/Courses/GradCourseDescriptions.html#CS5914). 

**Accolades and Leadership((

Dimitrios's excellence in his field is recognized by his status as an [IEEE Fellow](https://www.ieee.org/membership/fellows/index.html), a [Royal Society Wolfson Fellow](https://royalsociety.org/grants-schemes-awards/grants/royal-society-wolfson-fellowship/), and Fellowships of the [AAIA](https://www.aaia-ai.org/fellows), [British Computer Society](https://www.bcs.org/membership-and-registrations/become-a-member/bcs-fellowship/), a [the Institute of Engineering and Technology](https://www.theiet.org/membership/become-a-member/fellow-membership/), alongside being a [Distinguished Member of the ACM](https://awards.acm.org/distinguished-members) and a [Distinguished Visitor of the IEEE Computer Society](https://www.computer.org/communities/professional-chapters/distinguished-visitors-program). His prestigious awards include the NSF CAREER, DOE Early Career, IBM Faculty Award, Cisco Faculty Award, Sony Faculty Innovation Award, SFI-DEL Investigator Award, and the Marie Curie Individual Fellowship, among others. His research excellence has also been recognized with nine best paper awards from premier conferences (including SC, PPoPP, IPDPS, CCGRID, and DATE), three Best Paper Award nominations (ICS, SC, and HPDC) and two editorial excellence awards from the [IEEE Transactions on Parallel and Distributed Systems](https://ieeexplore.ieee.org/xpl/RecentIssue.jsp?punumber=71) and [Sustainable Computing: Informatics and Systems](https://www.sciencedirect.com/journal/sustainable-computing-informatics-and-systems)). 
His research has been supported with $36.5 million of external funding (personal share of a total of $103.7 million in competitive funding) from NSF, DOE, the European Commission, EPSRC, SFI, IBM, Cisco, and Sony.  More details can be found in his [CV](./cv.pdf)

In tems of service leadership, Dimitrios chairs the Steering Committee [ACM International Conference on Supercomputing (ICS)](https://www.ics-conference.org/) since June 2024. He has chaired the Steering Committee of the [IEEE International Conference on Performance Analysis of Systems and Software](https://ispass.org) in 2022 and 2023 and has served as Program Chair of [ICS](https://www.ics-conference.org) in 2022--2023 and [IEEE CCGRID](http://datasys.cs.iit.edu/events/CCGrid2014/) in 2014, as Program Area Chair of [SC](https://supercomputing.org) in 2014, [IPDPS](https://ipdps.org)in 2011, and [ICPP](https://www.icpp-conf.org/2007/) in 2007 and as General Chair of [IEEE ISPASS](https://www.ispass.org/ispass2018/) in 2018 and [IEEE Cluster](https://cluster2018.github.io/) in 2010 and 2018.  


**University Leadership and Diversity Initiatives:**

Dimitrios has held significant academic leadership roles, including the Head of the School of [EEECS at QUB](https://www.qub.ac.uk/schools/eeecs/), and Director of the [ECIT Global Innovation Institute](https://www.google.com/search?client=safari&rls=en&q=ECIT+QUB&ie=UTF-8&oe=UTF-8&safe=active). Under his leadership, the School of EEECS at QUB was honored with two awards fir enhancing diversity and inclusion, namely the ([Athena Swan Silver](https://www.advance-he.ac.uk/equality-charters/athena-swan-charter), and [Investors in People Silver](https://www.investorsinpeople.com)). 

**Current Endeavors:**

At present, Dimitrios leads the [PEARL (Performance of Emerging Architectures Laboratory)](https://www.linkedin.com/company/performance-of-emerging-architectures-laboratory/?viewAsMember=true) at Virginia Tech. He is also Associate Director of the [Stack@CS Center for Computer Systems](https://www.google.com/search?client=safari&rls=en&q=Stack%40CS+VT&ie=UTF-8&oe=UTF-8&safe=active). His mission is to foster convergent research that integrates the design of computing system stacks with the design of science and engineering artifacts to address deep scientific questions and pressing societal needs.

Dimitrios is on the lookout for driven Ph.D. students to join PEARL. The laboratory is for students who are passionate about high-performance computing, computer systems, and tackling the intricate challenges that emerge 
in the design of computing systems stacks for cutting-edge applications. Prospective 
students are encouraged to reach out with a synopsis of their research interests and any pertinent experience.

Moreover, PEARL extends opportunities for MSc (with thesis option), Undergraduate, and High School students to engage in term internships, providing a platform for experiential learning and research.
